recordings.loc: Lambert, Tallahatchie County, Mississippi
recordings.rmk:
Natural sound. Bird foraging along a drainage ditch in early succession trees approximately 1-2m above the ground and 5m from me. No large trees in within a quarter mile. Tallest vegetation ~5m, and most ~3m or less. Good Painted Bunting habitat generally.  Same individual as XC315083.

#Habitat#
National Wildlife Refuge consisting of converted aquaculture ponds, some bottomland hardwood, and flooded agricultural fields. Primary area is a series of ~20 aquaculture ponds managed for waterfowl and shorebirds, surrounded by trees. A diversion canal of the Tallahatchie River runs along the eastern boundary. 

#Editing#
Edited in Adobe Audition. Butterworth high-pass filter, order 3, cutoff frequency 800 Hz

#Equipment#
Fostex FR-2 digital recorder with Sennheiser microphone and Telinga pro 22" parabolic reflector.

recordings.loc: Yard, Croton, New York
recordings.rmk: I seem to be having some trouble with warblers this year. This chip sounds somewhat like a Hooded Warbler, which I think I may have heard this morning, and somewhat like a Redstart / Yellow / Blackpoll Warbler, all of which I've positively heard. I can't really tell. I know that this is identified with no problem on the spectrogram, but I can't use them. I also know the chip itself is not as clear and crisp as the Hooded but I think it also lacks allll of the frequencies of the other chip.
